      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Bernoulli's principle, in the context of an airfoil, is a bit like a clever trick played by a clever little goblin. Imagine the airfoil as a flat, smooth surface, like a giant pancake, but with a twist. The top surface of the airfoil is shaped like a gentle hill, while the bottom surface is like a steep valley. When air flows over the airfoil, the goblin's trick comes into play.\n\nThe goblin speeds up the air flowing over the top of the hill (the curved surface of the airfoil), while slowing it down on the steep valley (the flat surface). This is because the goblin likes to keep things moving quickly, but he also knows that when things move faster, they spread out and become thinner, like a crowd of goblins rushing to escape a giant's clutches.\n\nNow, here's where the magic happens. The faster, thinner air on top of the airfoil creates a lower pressure compared to the slower, thicker air below. This pressure difference, like a mischievous goblin's invisible hand, pushes the airfoil upwards, giving the plane the lift it needs to take off from the ground. The goblin's trick, played by Bernoulli",
